      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! Normalizing your features is crucial because it ensures that the learning process isn't biased by the magnitude of the values. When one feature is on a 0–1 scale and another is on a 1000–5000 scale, the gradient-based optimization algorithms (like gradient descent) will converge much more efficiently if the input space is roughly uniform. Mathematically, this helps the loss landscape become smoother and more isotropic, allowing the model to learn faster and more stably.\n\nThink of it like a goblin who has to carry two weights: one is a tiny feather, the other is a heavy stone. If the goblin tries to lift them at the same time, the stone will dominate the motion, making the goblin's movement erratic. By normalizing the weights so they are both roughly the same size, the goblin can balance the effort and move more smoothly. In your model, normalization does the same thing, making the learning process more balanced and efficient.\n\n**Why it matters for the math**\n\n1. **Gradient Magnitude**  \n   In gradient descent, the update step is proportional to the gradient of the loss with respect to each parameter. If one feature has a much",
