      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When one feature has a much larger scale than the others, the gradients computed during backpropagation will be disproportionately weighted toward that feature. In gradient descent, the parameter update is proportional to the gradient, so a large-scale feature can cause the optimization step to be dominated by that feature, making the convergence slow or unstable. By normalizing the features to a similar range, you balance the gradient magnitudes across all inputs. This results in a smoother loss landscape, allowing the optimizer to take more consistent steps toward the minimum.\n\nIn mathematical terms, the gradient of the loss function \\(L\\) with respect to the weights \\(w\\) is \\(\\nabla_w L = \\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial w}\\). If the inputs \\(x\\) vary widely in scale, the term \\(\\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial w}\\) will have components that are proportional to the input values. Normalizing the inputs (e.g., via standardization or min-max scaling) ensures that each component of the gradient contributes roughly equally, leading to a more isotropic loss surface and faster convergence.",
